As required, different amounts of materials were mixed to get a reaction system with respective concentrations of 0–200 μM furfural, 20 μL/mL of o-CDs, 16 mM of TMEDA, and 3 mM of APS in H3BO3–NaOH buffer (10 mM, pH = 8.5), respectively. After 1h reaction at room temperature (RT), the fluorescence spectrum (λex = 410 nm) of each solution was collected. Finally, a plot of fluorescence intensity at 520 nm (I

                           520
                        ) versus furfural concentration was generated, and a linear equation was evaluated accordingly.

Inspired to employ this method for furfural detection, we examined the emission spectra of o-CDs-TA at various furfural concentrations (Fig. 3c). Since o-CDs-TA-F have the best stability and fluorescence intensity in H3BO3–NaOH buffer at pH 8.5 (Figure S3), it was chosen as the solution for furfural detection. Along with the concentration of furfural increased, the peak position of o-CDs-TA shifted from 570 nm to 520 nm, with concurrent intensity enhancements and a color transition from orange to green (Fig. 3d). Consequently, a linear relationship between the emission enhancement at 520 nm (I–I

                           0
                        ) and the furfural concentrations across a wide range of 10–200 μM was established (Fig. 3e). According to the rule of 3σ/k [48], a low limit of detection (LOD) of 30.5 nM was achieved for furfural. Moreover, the corresponding changes in CIE chromaticity based on the fluorescence emission are also presented (Fig. 3f), enabling the naked-eye detection of furfural using UV light as an excitation source.
